cuts... so why back out?  The problem is that more and more people<br>
believe it to be faked.  Especially as younger generations, who weren't<br>
even born when the last moon mission took place believe it...<br>
afterall, they weren't born into that era... all they have known<br>
is the space shuttle! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/26/02 3:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=666.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Should NASA continue with moon hoax debunking book?</span><hr size=1> I was not alive at the time of the Moon Landings, but am 99.9% sure they occurred.  The thing is everyone loves a big conspiracy and what is bigger than the Apollo program?  It is sickening sometimes how they try to paint NASA and the aministration as liars.  I mean, I may not agree NASA politics, but unfounded accusations are disgusting.  I agree that this myth needs to be rebuffed.  If people use a little common sense, they should see that Apollo did happen.<br>
<br>
However, I think an issue even more pressing is that the space program and humanity in general has been in decline since the 1970s.  We have lost a sense of adventure and a need for progress.  We have become complacent and believe we have found everything important.  All of this has led to many becoming elitist and taking the very technologies that allowed them to be alive for granted.  As long as we do not push forward, we will fall back.  The space program is an excellent vehicle to combat this decline.  <br>
<br>
